## 16-Bit Machine Code Emulator CPU

This is a 16-bit CPU emulator where the user can type machine code (hexadecimal) into 'CPUMemory.txt' to type commands.

I wanted to undergo a project to deepen my understanding of computer hardware, which led me to making my own CPU. Originally, this was done in Logisim. But that CPU was hard to implement and was only an 8-bit CPU. The idea to create my second CPU creation on Python originated from the inherent ability of easy implementation and ease of access. If I could make a second CPU on Python, it could run on practically any device with an OS. In this case, I traded complexity to make sure other users could easily use this program.

## Features

- Emulates a 16-bit CPU with general and special-purpose registers.
- Supports basic arithmetic, logic, memory, stack, and control flow instructions.
- Easy to enter and execute custom machine code.
- Fully documented instruction set in `InstructionSetGuide.txt`.

### Installation

1. Clone this repository:

    git clone https://github.com/kingjakob37/16-bit-cpu-emulator.git

2. Navigate to the project folder:

    cd 16-bit-cpu-emulator

3. Run the emulator:

    python cpu_emulator.py

## Usage

1. Open `CPUMemory.txt`.
2. You will see a pre-filled example demonstrating basic usage of the emulator:

    80f0    # Load 240 into Reg. A
    8132    # Load 50 into Reg. B
    1010    # Add Reg. A and Reg. B

3. Modify or add your own machine code instructions in hexadecimal format.
4. Save the file.
5. Run the emulator to execute your code.
6. Refer to `InstructionSetGuide.txt` for a detailed description of all instructions, registers, flags, and conditional operations.
